<handout xml:id="handout-section-5-5-complex-eigenvalues">
  <title>Section 5.5: Complex Numbers and Complex Eigenvalues</title>

  <page xml:id="p-5-5-overview">
    <title>Overview</title>

    <objectives xml:id="obj-5-5-topics-goals">
      <title>Topics</title>
      <ul>
        <li>Complex numbers: addition, multiplication, complex conjugate</li>
        <li>Complex eigenvalues and eigenvectors</li>
        <li>Eigenvalue theorems</li>
      </ul>

      <p><em>Goals</em></p>
      <ul>
        <li>Use eigenvalues to identify the rotation and dilation of a linear transform.</li>
        <li>Recognize rotation–dilation matrices.</li>
        <li>Find complex eigenvalues and eigenvectors of a real matrix.</li>
        <li>Apply theorems to characterize matrices with complex eigenvalues.</li>
      </ul>

      <p><em>Motivating Question</em></p>
      <p>What are the eigenvalues of a rotation matrix?</p>
    </objectives>
  </page>


  <page xml:id="p-5-5-imaginary-numbers">
    <title>Imaginary Numbers</title>

    <p><em>Recall:</em> When solving polynomial equations, we may encounter square roots of negative numbers. For example:</p>

    <me>x^2 + 1 = 0.</me>

    <p>The roots of this equation are:</p>
    <example xml:id="ex-5-5-roots-x2plus1" workspace="true">
      <title>Compute the Roots</title>
      <statement>
        <p>Find the two solutions and write each in the form <m>a+bi</m>.</p>
      </statement>
    </example>

    <p>We usually write <m>\sqrt{-1}</m> as <m>i</m> (for “imaginary”).</p>
  </page>


  <page xml:id="p-5-5-addition-multiplication">
    <title>Addition and Multiplication in <m>\mathbb{C}</m></title>

    <p>
      The complex numbers are denoted by <m>\mathbb{C}</m>, where
    </p>

    <me>
      \mathbb{C}=\{\,a+bi \mid a,b\in\mathbb{R}\,\}.
    </me>

    <p>We can identify <m>\mathbb{C}</m> with <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m> via <m>a+bi \leftrightarrow (a,b)</m>.</p>

    <example xml:id="ex-5-5-add-mul" workspace="true">
      <title>Addition and Multiplication</title>
      <statement>
        <p>Compute:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><m>(2-3i)+(-1+i)=\ \square</m></li>
          <li><m>(2-3i)(-1+i)=\ \square</m></li>
        </ol>
      </statement>
    </example>
  </page>


  <page xml:id="p-5-5-conjugate-abs-polar">
    <title>Complex Conjugate, Absolute Value, and Polar Form</title>

    <definition xml:id="def-conjugate">
      <title>Complex Conjugate</title>
      <statement>
        <p>The conjugate of <m>a+bi</m> is <m>\overline{a+bi}=a-bi</m>.</p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <p><nbsp/></p>

    <definition xml:id="def-abs">
      <title>Absolute Value (Modulus)</title>
      <statement>
        <p>The absolute value (modulus) of <m>a+bi</m> is <m>\lvert a+bi\rvert=\sqrt{a^2+b^2}</m>.</p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <p><nbsp/></p>

    <p>
      We can write complex numbers in <em>polar form</em>:
      <m>a+bi = r(\cos\phi + i\sin\phi)</m>, where <m>r=\lvert a+bi\rvert</m> and <m>\phi</m> is the argument.
    </p>

    <example xml:id="ex-5-5-conj-mod-polar" workspace="true">
      <title>Practice</title>
      <statement>
        <p>Given <m>z=3-4i</m>, compute <m>\overline{z}</m>, <m>\lvert z\rvert</m>, and the polar form of <m>z</m>.</p>
      </statement>
    </example>
  </page>


  <page xml:id="p-5-5-conjugate-properties">
    <title>Conjugate Properties</title>

    <p>If <m>x,y\in\mathbb{C}</m> and <m>\vec v\in\mathbb{C}^n</m>, it can be shown that:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><m>\overline{x+y}=\overline{x}+\overline{y}</m></li>
      <li><m>\overline{A\vec v}=A\,\overline{\vec v}</m> (for a real matrix <m>A</m>)</li>
      <li><m>\operatorname{Im}(x\overline{x})=0</m></li>
    </ul>

    <example xml:id="ex-5-5-conjugate-product" workspace="true">
      <title>True or False?</title>
      <statement>
        <p>True or false: if <m>x,y\in\mathbb{C}</m>, then <m>\overline{xy}=\overline{x}\,\overline{y}</m>. Justify.</p>
      </statement>
    </example>
  </page>


  <page xml:id="p-5-5-conjugation-geometry">
    <title>Polar Form and the Complex Conjugate</title>

    <p>Conjugation reflects points across the real axis.</p>

    <image xml:id="img-5-5-conjugate-reflection">
      <latex-image>
        <latex>
\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.9]
  \coordinate (Origin)   at (0,0);
  \coordinate (XAxisMin) at (-1,0);
  \coordinate (XAxisMax) at (4,0);
  \coordinate (YAxisMin) at (0,-2.5);
  \coordinate (YAxisMax) at (0,2.5);
  \draw [thin, black,-&gt;] (XAxisMin) -- (XAxisMax) node [below left] {Re$(z)$};
  \draw [thin, black,-&gt;] (YAxisMin) -- (YAxisMax) node [below left] {Im$(z)$};
  \coordinate (Vone) at (3,2);
  \coordinate (Vtwo) at (3,-2);
  \draw [very thick,-&gt;,DarkBlue] (Origin) -- (Vone) node [above left] {$z=x+iy$};
  \draw [very thick,-&gt;,DarkRed] (Origin) -- (Vtwo) node [below left] {$\bar z=x-iy$};
  \draw[DarkBlue,dashed] (1,0) arc (0:35:1);
  \draw[DarkRed,dashed] (1,0) arc (0:-35:1);
  \draw[DarkRed] (1.5,-0.4) node {$-\phi$};
  \draw[DarkBlue] (1.5,0.4) node {$\phi$};
  \draw[black] (-0.4,-0.4) node {O};
\end{tikzpicture}
        </latex>
      </latex-image>
      <shortdescription>Diagram showing complex conjugation as reflection over real axis.</shortdescription>
      <description>
        The point <m>z=x+iy</m> at angle <m>\phi</m> reflects to <m>\overline{z}=x-iy</m> at angle <m>-\phi</m> across the real axis.
      </description>
    </image>
  </page>


  <page xml:id="p-5-5-euler-formula">
    <title>Euler’s Formula and Products in Polar Form</title>

    <p>
      Suppose <m>z_1</m> has angle <m>\phi_1</m> and <m>z_2</m> has angle <m>\phi_2</m>. In polar form with Euler’s formula, <m>z=r e^{i\phi}</m>.
    </p>

    <image xml:id="img-5-5-polar-angles">
      <latex-image>
        <latex>
\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.85]
  \coordinate (Origin)   at (0,0);
  \coordinate (XAxisMin) at (-2,0);
  \coordinate (XAxisMax) at (4,0);
  \coordinate (YAxisMin) at (0,-1);
  \coordinate (YAxisMax) at (0,2.5);
  \draw [thin, black,-&gt;] (XAxisMin) -- (XAxisMax) node [below left] {Re$(z)$};
  \draw [thin, black,-&gt;] (YAxisMin) -- (YAxisMax) node [above right] {Im$(z)$};
  \coordinate (Vone) at (2,1.3);
  \coordinate (Vtwo) at (0.5,1.2);
  \coordinate (Vthr) at (-0.56,3.05);
  \draw [very thick,-&gt;,DarkBlue] (Origin) -- (Vone) node [above] {$z_1$};
  \draw [very thick,-&gt;,red] (Origin) -- (Vtwo) node [above] {$z_2$};
  \draw [very thick,-&gt;,DarkGreen] (Origin) -- (Vthr) node [left] {$z_3$};
  \draw[DarkBlue] (1.2,0) arc (0:40:1);
  \draw[red] (1.0,0) arc (0:70:1);
  \draw[DarkGreen] (0.8,0) arc (0:90:1);
  \draw[DarkBlue] (1.5,0.3) node {$\phi_1$};
  \draw[red] (1,1) node {$\phi_2$};
  \draw[black] (-0.4,-0.4) node {O};
\end{tikzpicture}
        </latex>
      </latex-image>
      <shortdescription>Angles in polar form for complex numbers and their product.</shortdescription>
      <description>
        Vectors representing <m>z_1</m>, <m>z_2</m>, and their product <m>z_3=z_1z_2</m> with angles adding: <m>\phi_3=\phi_1+\phi_2</m>.
      </description>
    </image>

    <p>
      The product <m>z_1z_2</m> has angle <m>\phi_1+\phi_2</m> and modulus <m>\lvert z_1\rvert\lvert z_2\rvert</m>:
    </p>

    <me>
      z_3=z_1z_2=(\lvert z_1\rvert e^{i\phi_1})(\lvert z_2\rvert e^{i\phi_2})
      = \lvert z_1\rvert \lvert z_2\rvert e^{i(\phi_1+\phi_2)}.
    </me>
  </page>


  <page xml:id="p-5-5-complex-and-polynomials">
    <title>Complex Numbers and Polynomials</title>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-fta">
      <title>Fundamental Theorem of Algebra</title>
      <statement>
        <p>Every polynomial of degree <m>n</m> has exactly <m>n</m> complex roots, counting multiplicity.</p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>

    <p><nbsp/></p>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-conjugate-roots">
      <title>Conjugate Pairs for Real Coefficients</title>
      <statement>
        <ol>
          <li>If <m>\lambda\in\mathbb{C}</m> is a root of a real polynomial <m>p(x)</m>, then <m>\overline{\lambda}</m> is also a root.</li>
          <li>If <m>\lambda</m> is an eigenvalue of a real matrix <m>A</m> with eigenvector <m>\vec v</m>, then <m>\overline{\lambda}</m> is an eigenvalue of <m>A</m> with eigenvector <m>\overline{\vec v}</m>.</li>
        </ol>
      </statement>
    </theorem>

    <p><nbsp/></p>

    <example xml:id="ex-5-5-complete-eigs" workspace="true">
      <title>Complete the Eigenvalue List</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Four eigenvalues of a <m>7\times 7</m> real matrix are <m>-2</m>, <m>4+i</m>, <m>-4-i</m>, and <m>i</m>. What are the other eigenvalues?
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
  </page>


  <page xml:id="p-5-5-rotation-dilation">
    <title>Rotation–Dilation Matrices and Eigenvalues</title>

    <example xml:id="ex-5-5-rot-dil-eigs" workspace="true">
      <title>Rotation by <m>\pi/4</m> and Dilation by <m>\sqrt{2}</m></title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The matrix that rotates vectors by <m>\phi=\pi/4</m> about the origin and then scales by <m>r=\sqrt{2}</m> is
        </p>
        <me>
          A=
          \begin{bmatrix}
            r \amp 0\\
            0 \amp r
          \end{bmatrix}
          \begin{bmatrix}
            \cos\phi \amp -\sin\phi\\
            \sin\phi \amp \cos\phi
          \end{bmatrix}
          =
          \begin{bmatrix}
            1 \amp -1\\
            1 \amp 1
          \end{bmatrix}.
        </me>
        <p>Find the eigenvalues of <m>A</m> and one eigenvector for each eigenvalue.</p>
      </statement>
    </example>
  </page>


  <page xml:id="p-5-5-rotation-dilation-general">
    <title>General Rotation–Dilation Form</title>

    <p>
      The previous example is a special case of the real <em>rotation–dilation</em> form
      <m>C=\begin{bmatrix} a \amp -b\\ b \amp a \end{bmatrix}</m>.
    </p>

    <example xml:id="ex-5-5-C-eigs-polar-1" workspace="true">
      <title>Eigenvalues in Polar Form (I)</title>
      <statement>
        <p>Compute the eigenvalues of</p>
        <me>
          C=\begin{bmatrix} a \amp -b\\ b \amp a \end{bmatrix}
        </me>
        <p>and express them in polar form <m>re^{i\phi}</m>.</p>
      </statement>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="ex-5-5-C-eigs-polar-2" workspace="true">
      <title>Eigenvalues in Polar Form (II)</title>
      <statement>
        <p>Repeat the computation and confirm the conjugate-pair structure.</p>
      </statement>
    </example>
  </page>


  <page xml:id="p-5-5-complex-eigs-example">
    <title>Finding Complex Eigenpairs</title>

    <example xml:id="ex-5-5-complex-eigs" workspace="true">
      <title>Example: Complex Eigenpairs of a Real Matrix</title>
      <statement>
        <p>Find the complex eigenvalues and an associated complex eigenvector for each eigenvalue of</p>
        <me>
          A=\begin{bmatrix}
            1 \amp -2\\
            1 \amp 3
          \end{bmatrix}.
        </me>
      </statement>
    </example>
  </page>

</handout>